    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Service Manual - Power Cylinder - Installation - Connecting Rod and Piston Installation
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26507.3.2" svcproctype="install" graphiccount="7">
        <title>Connecting Rod and Piston Installation</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn crankshaft so that the number 1 connecting rod journal is at the bottom of its
                stroke.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Before installing piston and connecting rod assembly, make sure all piston cooling tubes are in
                    place.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e300826" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0410.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Lubricating the piston and piston rings for installation</caption>
        </figure>
        <figure id="e300827" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd06/D0613.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Lubricating the cylinder walls for piston installation</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Coat piston and piston rings with clean engine oil. Coat cylinder walls, crankshaft
                journals, and piston cope with clean engine oil.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, the "CAM V8" stamped on top of the piston must be oriented towards the
                    camshaft side of the crankcase, toward center of engine.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>The pistons are interchangeable between the VT 365 and VT 275 diesel engines. The initial VT 275
                    engine build used the same piston as the VT 365 engine. Therefore, a piston stamped with "CAM V8" on
                    top is correct for both engines.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e300828" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ08/J08057.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston rings compressed in piston cope</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place piston in Piston Ring Compressor (cope) to compress rings and ease the installation of
                piston / connecting rod assembly into the crankcase. See
                <hotlnk document="eges3001_167.xml" xrefid="E3008C">Special Service Tools</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Make certain that connecting rod and cap bearing surfaces have been wiped clean of any oil or
                    residue.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install bearing shells in connecting rod and cap. Coat bearing shell in connecting rod with
                clean engine oil.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Carefully insert connecting rod and start piston into the top end of the cylinder bore until
                cope is against the top of the cylinder.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, use caution not to damage piston cooling tubes when installing
                    connecting rod and piston assemblies.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e300829" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0411.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Installing the piston into the cylinder bore</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Once piston and connecting rod assembly have been inserted in cylinder bore, use the handle
                (wood or plastic) of a hammer to tap piston in crankcase bore. Guide connecting rod in place on
                crankshaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300830" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ04/J04008.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Proper orientation of piston installed in cylinder bore</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Identification mark, "CAM V8"</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply clean engine oil to connecting rod bolt hole threads and bearing shell in cap before
                installing bolts.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="e300831" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0412.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Connecting rod and cap matching identification numbers</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Matching numbers</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not alter or damage the fractured mating surfaces of the connecting
                    rod and cap.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Assemble cap to connecting rod with matching identification code on same crankshaft journal
                from which it was removed. Be certain that the longer leg of the connecting rod and the "CAM V8" stamp
                on piston crown are oriented towards the camshaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not use air powered tools when installing connecting rod bolts. This
                    may cause seizure of connecting rod bolts.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="e300832" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figJ04/J04009.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Torquing the connecting rod cap</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod bearing cap</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod bolt</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install and tighten connecting rod bolts evenly to the initial and final torque values. See
                <hotlnk document="eges3001_166.xml" xrefid="E3008B">Special Torque</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Repeat installation procedure for remaining connecting rod and piston assemblies.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check connecting rod side clearance with feeler gauge. See procedure in removal section
                Piston and Connecting Rod Checks in this section.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Complete the engine rebuild and reinstall all safety guards, shields and covers after
                servicing the engine.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Make sure all tools, covers, loose parts and service equipment are removed from the engine
                area after all work is done.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
